		<a name="37219"></a>
		<img src="icon_posticon.gif" border="0" hspace="3"><font color="white" face="Verdana" size="2">Posted&nbsp;-&nbsp;06/07/2002&nbsp;:&nbsp; 23:20:18</font>

		&nbsp;<a href="pop_profile.asp?mode=display&amp;id=2542"><img src="icon_profile.gif" height="15" width="15" alt="Show Profile" border="0" align="absmiddle" hspace="6"></a>
        
			&nbsp;<a href="JavaScript:openWindow('pop_mail.asp?id=2542')"><img src="icon_email.gif" height="15" width="15" alt="Email Poster" border="0" align="absmiddle" hspace="6"></a>

        &nbsp;<a href="post.asp?method=ReplyQuote&amp;REPLY_ID=37219&amp;TOPIC_ID=4375&amp;FORUM_ID=2&amp;CAT_ID=1&amp;Forum_Title=General+Discussions&amp;Topic_Title=Do+necros+and+pvp+mix%2E%2E%2E&amp;M="><img src="icon_reply_topic.gif" height="15" width="15" alt="Reply with Quote" border="0" align="absmiddle" hspace="6"></a>

        <hr noshade size="2" color="#545A7D">
        
         <BLOCKQUOTE id=quote><font size=1 face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" id=quote>quote:<hr height=1 noshade id=quote>Cerilius obviously belongs to those 90% who can't pvp. And enchanter is PATHETIC in PvP, unless he is in the right zone. For now, let's assume this is all taking place in the arena.</P><P>First of all, even assuming that the ench drains the necro oom and that the necro doesn't hurt the enchanter at all throught the whole time (lol yeah good one); assuming this, what's an enchanter going to do next? Melee the necro to death? I got dibs on the necro in that case.<hr height=1 noshade id=quote></BLOCKQUOTE id=quote></font id=quote><font face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" size=2 id=quote></P><P>Or how about summoning a level 55 animation and giving it Bedlam and Resist Magic? Even if it's not a guaranteed kill (if the pet doesn't run at jboots speed, the necro can always get away), it's enough offense to win the fight (if we're talking about a duel in the arena).</P><P><BLOCKQUOTE id=quote><font size=1 face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" id=quote>quote:<hr height=1 noshade id=quote>Second, lets say the enchanter's last buff is rune 5, and he has 2 slots open and has 2 instaclick items. First off, chances are that the enchanter doesn't have cancel magic memorized, instead he has recant.<hr height=1 noshade id=quote></BLOCKQUOTE id=quote></font id=quote><font face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" size=2 id=quote></P><P>Then "chances are" that enchanter is an idiot. The ability of a *good* enchanter to beat a necro is what Saleem and others have been calling into question. So, let's assume hereafter that the he has *both* Nullify Magic and Recant Magic memorized at the same time. (As a reminder, Nullify takes off two buffs -- not one -- and Recant takes off four.)</P><P><BLOCKQUOTE id=quote><font size=1 face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" id=quote>quote:<hr height=1 noshade id=quote>You quickly pop off some debufs, 3 in a row, the enchanter (if using cancel) dispells one but the other two fill up the slots and you can debuff or dot at will then. If he uses recant (much more likely) he will start taking off his own buffs.<hr height=1 noshade id=quote></BLOCKQUOTE id=quote></font id=quote><font face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" size=2 id=quote></P><P>I recommend you go back and reread my earlier post where I address the debuff tactic you're referring to, and how it can be circumvented.</P><P>If, like you mention, the enchanter has two instaclick items (goblin earring and jboots, let's say), his ideal buff list will look like this:</P><P>[Grim Aura]<BR>[Jboots]<BR>Nothing<BR>Nothing<BR>[Crap buff]<BR>[Crap buff]<BR>[Crap buff]<BR>. . .<BR>[Good buffs]<BR>. . .<BR>[Rune V]</P><P>See those two empty spaces under Grim Aura and Jboots? If the necro were to lead with debuffs (Siphon Strength and Shadow Vortex, say) they would fall into those two empty slots. The enchanter would then CLICK OFF the Grim Aura effect and wait for a dot to be cast. After that, he would simply Recant himself, taking off the dot, jboots, Siphon Strength, and Shadow Vortex, and then hit his earring and jboots again, so his buff list will remain unharmed and still look like the one above.</P><P>If the debuffs were skipped and a dot was cast, the enchanter would simply click off Grim Aura and cast Nullify Magic.</P><P><BLOCKQUOTE id=quote><font size=1 face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" id=quote>quote:<hr height=1 noshade id=quote>Remember, while he is doing all that you are free to do whatever you want -- dot some more or get a pet. As to the enchanter poofing the pet, that can take up to 8 minutes.<hr height=1 noshade id=quote></BLOCKQUOTE id=quote></font id=quote><font face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" size=2 id=quote></P><P>You're only "free to do what you want" for the three seconds it takes the enchanter to pillage himself. If you dot some more, he'll continue to dispel your dots -- faster than you can stack them -- and you will eventually run out of mana. And don't forget that your pets take 14 seconds to cast. With 11 seconds to spare after pillaging himself, he will have plenty of time to cast Chaotic Feedback on you to interrupt, perhaps even after a quick Mana Sieve.</P><P>Even if you did manage to get a pet up somehow, the enchanter will simply charm the pet and wait for it to poof. (Not having played an enchanter, I'll assume for the sake of arugment that you can't dispel off your own charm to poof the pet faster.) Like you mentioned, that can take up to 8 minutes. So what? Does the enchanter LOSE because of this? The surprising answer is *no*. Soon, I'll show how he doesn't.</P><P><BLOCKQUOTE id=quote><font size=1 face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" id=quote>quote:<hr height=1 noshade id=quote>So the enchanter tries to cast on the pet, and you know what that gives you? More time.<hr height=1 noshade id=quote></BLOCKQUOTE id=quote></font id=quote><font face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" size=2 id=quote></P><P>8 seconds, to be precise. If the enchanter is a skilled player, he'll take advantage of the fact that your pet runs slower than jboots. First, he'll run in a straight line away from you and the pet (during which time you can't land a single spell besides possibly one Deflux), get some distance, root the pet (2 seconds), hit jboots to refresh his spell gems, and charm the pet (6 seconds). (Notice that if you dispelled root, his charm would still hit your pet before it reached him.) During those 8 seconds, you can take 5.5 seconds to cast Pyrocuror and be 2.5 seconds mid-way through your next dot. At this point, the enchanter will begin to cast Recant on himself, and after you land Splurt/Vexing/whatever under Pyrocuror, both dots will *immediately* get dispelled. The enchanter then just clicks his earring and his jboots again, and his buff list looks as good as new. Now the clock is ticking for your charmed pet, you just wasted ~600 mana, and -- if you were lucky -- you managed to do a feeble 80 damage to the enchanter with the first tick of Pyrocuror.</P><P><BLOCKQUOTE id=quote><font size=1 face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" id=quote>quote:<hr height=1 noshade id=quote>While he is trying to mez/root the pet, you keep casting dots, so your last dots are definetly in the last slots.<hr height=1 noshade id=quote></BLOCKQUOTE id=quote></font id=quote><font face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" size=2 id=quote></P><P>Always be careful when using a word like "definitely". In our case, the necro's pet at this point is ALREADY CHARMED. No additional mezzing/rooting is needed. But ignoring this fact for a moment, you need to realize that given our hypothetical enchanter's buff setup, it would take *at least* 15 seconds to "definitely" get a dot below the enchanter's buff list (jboot-refreshing taken into account), and that's if he's too stupid to pillage himself in the meantime. On the other hand, it only takes 2 seconds to root a pet and 2.5 seconds to mez it. You're distorting time to make it look like the necro would win. It's like saying "Oh, and while the enchanter is rooting the pet you can drop Splurt, Pyro and Vexing all on him at once before he gets ready to cast his next spell."</P><P><BLOCKQUOTE id=quote><font size=1 face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" id=quote>quote:<hr height=1 noshade id=quote>So he has to dispell himself. Chances are he'll click off every buff he can and the chain-recant, right?<hr height=1 noshade id=quote></BLOCKQUOTE id=quote></font id=quote><font face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" size=2 id=quote></P><P>If so, then "chances are" he didn't manage his buff list correctly. Let me remind you, Angrier, that this is a hypothetical fight between a *perfect* enchanter and a *perfect* necro. Saying "chances are" followed by whatever you want to happen in the fight doesn't cut it in an argument like this.</P><P><BLOCKQUOTE id=quote><font size=1 face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" id=quote>quote:<hr height=1 noshade id=quote>Notice, throughout this whole time the enchanter didn't have a moment to spare for a mana sieve, let alone refresh bedlam/rune. And you are saying that the enchanter will win.<hr height=1 noshade id=quote></BLOCKQUOTE id=quote></font id=quote><font face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" size=2 id=quote></P><P>The enchanter *would* win. The picture you portrayed was that of an average necro fighting a bad enchanter. If it takes 8 minutes for a charmed pet to poof, a good enchanter can stay alive during the ENTIRE 8 MINUTES just by keeping himself dispelled of dots and refreshing his rune after every three defluxes. (With two more instacast items, he could even afford to lose his rune completely before recasting it.) At the end of those 8 minutes, the enchanter will emerge with a buffed pet, a sizeable mana pool, and necro victim running around helpless and waiting to be killed.</P><P><BLOCKQUOTE id=quote><font size=1 face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" id=quote>quote:<hr height=1 noshade id=quote>Well all I can say is, thanks to people like Cerilius and Potus, people expect the necro to suck. Good thing, it makes it all the more easier for me to win.<hr height=1 noshade id=quote></BLOCKQUOTE id=quote></font id=quote><font face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" size=2 id=quote></P><P>Cerilius D`Nixx<BR>54 Necromancer<a href="#top"><img src="icon_go_up.gif" height="15" width="15" border="0" align="right" alt="Go to Top of Page"></a></font></td>
